Great question, Chris. In a monorepo with multiple microservices, the trick is to make it impossible (or at least very hard) for an LLM-driven “developer” to touch anything outside the service you’ve asked it to change. That means combining context isolation, filesystem/tool sandboxing, and guardrails in Git/CI. Below is a practical, layered approach you can implement incrementally.
1) Scope the LLM’s context so it never “sees” other services
Why: LLMs change what they can see. If you never feed it other services’ files, it won’t propose edits there.
How:
Service-scoped retrieval: When you do RAG/file loading, filter by path prefix, e.g. services/payments/**.
Put a monorepo.json manifest at repo root to map service → allowed paths:
JSON
{
"services": {
"payments": ["services/payments/**", "libs/payments-interfaces/**"],
"notifications": ["services/notifications/**"]
}
}
Your retriever filters embeddings or file loaders to those globs only.
Tool-side path allowlist: For any “read file” tool you expose to the LLM, enforce an allowlist derived from the manifest. If path not allowed → deny.
No global repo embedding: Use per-service vector indexes to avoid cross-service leakage.
2) Sandbox filesystem access for the LLM agent
Why: Even if it wants to, it shouldn’t be able to write elsewhere.
How:
Worktree or sparse checkout only for the target service:
Shell
# Option A: sparse checkout
git clone <repo> mono
cd mono
git sparse-checkout init --cone
git sparse-checkout set services/payments libs/payments-interfaces
Mount only this directory into the LLM’s container or tool process.
Chroot / container jail: Run the LLM code-mod tools in a container where /workspace is just the sparse path. No other paths mounted.
OS file permissions: Set the LLM runner user (e.g., llm-bot) to have write permissions only within the service directory.
3) Use per-service “developer agents” rather than a single repo-wide agent
Why: It clarifies ownership and prevents accidental cross-service changes.
How:
Run a payments-agent, notifications-agent, etc., each configured with:
Its own RAG index.
Its own file tools locked to path allowlists.
Its own build/test commands.
The orchestrator routes the task to the right agent (based on a service name in the user prompt or a routing step that maps features → service).
4) Put guardrails in Git: CODEOWNERS + protected branches + path protections
Why: Even if a change slips through, it won’t merge.
How (GitHub example):
CODEOWNERS:
services/payments/   @payments-team
libs/payments-interfaces/ @payments-team
Branch protection:
Require reviews from CODEOWNERS.
Block direct pushes to main.
Require status checks to pass (see CI below).
Path protection rules (GitHub/GitLab/Azure Repos):
Only the owning team (or bot) can change their paths.
Deny the LLM bot account outside its service paths.
Azure Repos / GitLab equivalents: Use path filters, approvals by code owners, Protected branches, and merge request rules similarly.
5) Enforce “path purity” in CI: fail any PR that touches disallowed paths
Why: Early automatic stop if the diff includes other services.
How:
A tiny CI job that loads monorepo.json, reads the PR diff, and fails if files outside allowed globs are present:
Shell
# pseudo
SERVICE="$TARGET_SERVICE" # set via pipeline var or PR label
ALLOWED=$(jq -r ".services[\"$SERVICE\"][ ]|.[]" monorepo.json)
git fetch origin "$PR_BRANCH"
git diff --name-only origin/main...HEAD > changed.txt
 
python - <<'PY'
import fnmatch, json, sys, os
service = os.environ["SERVICE"]
manifest = json.load(open("monorepo.json"))
allowed = manifest["services"][service]
changed = [l.strip() for l in open("changed.txt")]
disallowed = [f for f in changed if not any(fnmatch.fnmatch(f, pat) for pat in allowed)]
if disallowed:
print("Disallowed changes:", *disallowed, sep="\n- ")
sys.exit(1)
PY
