Make this a required status check for merging.
6) Validate at the tool layer: “pre-flight diff guard” before committing
Why: Provide immediate feedback to the LLM tool, not just at PR time.
How:
Wrap any “apply patch” tool with a validator:
Compute proposed changes (unified diff).
Reject if any file path fails the allowlist.
Return a structured error telling the agent to limit changes to allowed paths.
Example interface:
TypeScript
type ApplyPatchRequest = { service: "payments", diff: string }
type ApplyPatchResponse = { accepted: boolean, error?: string }
Implementation rejects if diff touches unauthorized files.
7) Approval gates and RBAC for the bot account
Why: Human-in-the-loop for safety.
How:
Separate bot identity per service (e.g., payments-bot). Give each bot:
Repo read globally
Write only to service paths (enforced via CI/branch rules)
Require human approvals from the service team (via CODEOWNERS) before merge.
8) PR hygiene: enforce service-scoped intent
Why: Make drift obvious and culturally unacceptable.
How:
PR template:
Markdown
### Target service
- [ ] payments
 
### Why only this service?
Explain the change. If shared code changes are needed, open a separate PR to the shared lib.
 
### Checklist
- [ ] Paths limited to service allowlist
- [ ] Service tests pass
- [ ] No cross-service imports added
Commit-msg hook requiring a Service: payments line, and CI validates it matches changed paths.
9) Shared libraries: provide an official path for cross-cutting changes
Why: Sometimes you do need shared updates; make that explicit and controlled.
How:
Maintain libs/* as shared modules with separate ownership and versioning.
If the LLM needs a shared change, require a separate PR to libs/* reviewed by the libs owners. The service PR depends on the new version (or monorepo tag).
10) Build/test isolation to discourage cross-service edits
Why: If the LLM changes other services, tests will fail loudly.
How:
Service-specific build pipelines:
Shell
# in CI for payments
pnpm -F @org/payments... test # or Bazel target //services/payments:tests
Tools like Bazel/Nx/Turborepo to compute affected targets; the LLM agent only runs affected:test --scope=payments.
11) IDE & editor ergonomics for LLM-assisted edits
Why: Prevent accidental “quick fixes” across the repo.
How:
VS Code Workspace with folders limited to the service paths for the bot/editor session.
files.exclude for other services.
Workspace Trust set so only the service subfolder is trusted for code actions.
12) Policy as Code for defense in depth
Why: Central, auditable rules.
How:
Use Open Policy Agent (OPA) or Conftest to enforce:
“PRs labeled service:payments must not change files outside allowed paths.”
“Bot payments-bot cannot touch non-payments paths.”
