Below is a clear, architecture‑level explanation of “service RAG”, written for someone designing or governing a monorepo, not just experimenting with prompts.
What is Service RAG?
Service RAG (Service‑Scoped Retrieval‑Augmented Generation) is a pattern where an LLM is allowed to retrieve context only from the code, docs, configs, and contracts that belong to a single microservice (and its explicitly declared dependencies)—and nothing else in the monorepo.
It is the RAG equivalent of bounded context in Domain‑Driven Design.
In short:
Service RAG ensures an LLM can reason like a service‑limited developer, not a repo‑god.
Why Service RAG exists (the core problem)
In a monorepo:
Everything is technically reachable
Shared models and utilities blur boundaries
LLMs try to be “helpful” by fixing problems globally
Without service‑scoped RAG, an LLM will:
Pull in DTOs from other services
“Improve” shared libraries
Refactor adjacent services for cleanliness
Copy patterns that violate service ownership
This is architecturally dangerous, especially in regulated estates like DWP.
Service RAG exists to enforce architectural intent at the AI level.
Service RAG vs Traditional RAG
Aspect
Traditional RAG
Service RAG
Retrieval scope
Whole repo / all docs
One service boundary
Indexing
Single global vector index
Multiple per‑service indexes
Prompt context
Mixed concerns
Bounded context only
Failure mode
Cross‑service changes
Narrow, local mistakes
Architectural alignment
Weak
Strong (DDD‑aligned)
Conceptual Model
Think in four layers:
┌────────────────────────────┐
│     User Request           │
│ "Change refunds logic"     │
└────────────┬───────────────┘
             ▼
┌────────────────────────────┐
│  Service Routing Layer     │
│ Identifies: payments       │
└────────────┬───────────────┘
             ▼
┌────────────────────────────┐
│     Service RAG Context    │
│  - payments code           │
│  - payments docs           │
│  - approved interfaces     │
└────────────┬───────────────┘
             ▼
┌────────────────────────────┐
│     LLM / Agent            │
│  Sees ONLY that context    │
└────────────────────────────┘
The LLM literally cannot know about other services unless you decide to include them.
What goes into a Service RAG?
A Service RAG index is built from intentionally selected artefacts.
✅ Included
services/payments/**
Service‑owned configs (application.yaml, Helm chart, etc.)
Service README / ADRs
Service tests
Explicit shared contracts:
OpenAPI specs
Protobufs / Avro schemas
Messaging event definitions
Shared libraries only if explicitly allow‑listed
❌ Excluded
Other services’ implementations
Their internal models
Global utilities unless explicitly allowed
Repo‑root “kitchen sink” docs
How Service RAG works (step‑by‑step)
1. Service identification
Before retrieval, the system must determine:
Target service(s)
Change intent
Examples:
Prompt explicitly says: “payments”
Repository metadata maps feature → service
Planner agent classifies request
This step is deterministic—not guessed by the main LLM.
2. Path‑based filtering
A hard boundary is applied before vector similarity:
Plain Text
Allowed paths:
services/payments/**
libs/payments-interfaces/**
Only files inside these paths are:
Loaded
Embedded
Queried
This prevents accidental “nearest neighbour” leakage from other services with similar vocabulary.
3. Service‑specific vector index
Each service has its own index:
/rag
├── payments.index
├── notifications.index
├── identity.index
Key properties:
Smaller → higher relevance
Faster retrieval
Cleaner semantic space
Safer outputs
This is the single biggest quality improvement you’ll see.
4. Intent‑aware retrieval
The retriever pulls:
Code relevant to the request
Documentation explaining why code exists
Tests that encode behavioural intent
Example query:
“refund partial settlement logic”
The retriever:
Prefers business rules over helpers
Pulls tests first (gold standard)
Avoids infra noise unless asked
5. Context assembly (prompt shaping)
The final LLM context typically includes:
Service description
Architectural constraints
Relevant files (trimmed)
Explicit rule:
“You MAY NOT propose changes outside these paths.”
This is defence in depth—even though file access is already restricted.
Why Service RAG works so well
1. Cognitive alignment
The LLM reasons like a single‑team developer instead of an omniscient outsider.
2. Architectural compliance by default
Boundaries are enforced before generation, not after review.
3. Safer automation
You can confidently allow:
Auto‑PRs
Autonomous refactors
CI‑triggered changes
4. Governance & auditability
You can prove:
What the model saw
Why it made a change
That no other service context influenced it
This matters in regulated environments.
Service RAG and shared libraries (important nuance)
Service RAG does not mean isolation from shared code—it means intentional inclusion.
Recommended pattern:
Shared libs have their own RAG index
Must be explicitly imported into a service RAG
Changes to shared code require a separate agent / PR
Example:
payments-rag:
  include:
    - services/payments/**
    - libs/money-types/**   # read-only
The LLM can use shared types but cannot modify them.
Service RAG vs “just telling the LLM in the prompt”
Why prompts alone are insufficient:
Prompt rule
Reality
“Don’t change other services”
LLM still sees them
“Only modify payments”
LLM still reasons globally
“Follow architecture”
LLM doesn’t know what it can’t see
Visibility = capability
Service RAG removes visibility, not just instruction.
How this fits your wider architecture work
Given your interests:
Agent‑to‑Agent
MCP
Federated systems
Tech debt remediation
Service RAG becomes the foundational safety primitive.
It enables:
