Service RAG for Dummies
(What you build, how it stays updated, how the LLM uses it, and how code changes happen safely)
Big picture (one minute version)
Think of Service RAG like this:
You don’t let the LLM “wander around” the service.
You pre‑pack a smart, searchable cheat‑sheet for each service, and the LLM can only consult that cheat‑sheet before writing code.
That cheat‑sheet is the RAG index.
PART 1 — What you’re actually building
Three things exist (nothing more):
A service folder (you already have this)
A service RAG index (new, read‑only)
A change executor (writes code, but with guards)
services/payments/        ← real code
rag/payments.index        ← searchable “memory”
change-runner             ← applies a patch safely
PART 2 — Creating the Service RAG (first time)
Step 1: Decide what “belongs” to the service
This is a human decision, not an LLM one.
Example for payments:
✅ Include:
services/payments/**
services/payments/README.md
services/payments/**/tests/**
libs/payments-interfaces/** (read‑only shared contracts)
❌ Exclude:
Other services
Old experiments
Global utils unless explicitly allowed
You write this down once in a manifest:
JSON
{
"service": "payments",
"include": [
"services/payments/**",
"libs/payments-interfaces/**"
]
}
This manifest is the law.
Step 2: Chop the code & docs into “chunks”
LLMs don’t read files — they read chunks.
Each chunk might be:
A function
A class
A test
A doc section
Example chunk metadata:
JSON
{
"id": "refunds-settlement-test",
"path": "services/payments/tests/refunds.test.ts",
"type": "test",
"service": "payments"
}
Chunks are:
Small (e.g. 200–800 tokens)
Self‑contained
Tagged with metadata (path, type, service)
Step 3: Turn chunks into embeddings (the “semantic fingerprints”)
Each chunk is converted into a vector (list of numbers).
You don’t need to care how — just know:
Similar meaning → similar vectors
Tests about refunds cluster together
Docs about settlement rules cluster together
These vectors are stored in:
rag/payments.index
This is read‑only memory.
📌 Important:
One index per service, not one big repo index.
Step 4: You now have a Service RAG
At this point:
Nothing magical
No autonomy
Just a fast lookup system saying:
“Given a question, which bits of this service matter?”
PART 3 — Keeping the RAG up to date
This part is boring (which is good).
When does RAG update?
Automatically on:
Merge to main
Release cut
Nightly job (optional)
What happens?
Changed files detected
Only affected chunks are re‑embedded
Index is updated in place
No humans involved.
💡 Key idea:
RAG is derived data, like build artefacts.
You never edit it directly.
PART 4 — How the LLM uses Service RAG (read‑only)
Now the interesting bit.
Step 1: You ask for a change
Example:
“Handle partial refunds properly in payments”
Step 2: Router decides which service this is for
This is deterministic, not guessed.
Intent: refunds
Service: payments
Only the payments RAG is touched.
Step 3: The LLM queries the RAG
The LLM asks something like:
