Service RAG shines for tweaks and refactoring, but initial design and first build is a different phase with different information needs.
Below is a high‑level, phase‑based mental model you can use without getting dragged into tooling detail.
Using LLMs for initial service design & build (high level)
Key idea up front
Initial design is not a Service‑RAG problem.
It’s a system‑level reasoning problem.
So the pattern changes by phase:
Phase
Scope
RAG type
1. Explore & design
Whole system
System / Domain RAG
2. Define boundaries
Service interfaces
Contract RAG
3. First build
Single service
Service RAG (seeded)
4. Evolution
Single service
Service RAG (normal)
You only lock down Service RAG after boundaries exist.
Phase 1: Explore & design (pre‑service)
What’s happening
You don’t even know what the services are yet.
You’re answering:
What problem exists?
What capabilities are needed?
Where are the seams?
What must not be coupled?
How the LLM is used
You allow wide context, deliberately.
Inputs look like:
Existing system docs
Legacy code excerpts
Policy / legislation
Business process descriptions
Event flows
Known pain points
⚠️ No service boundaries enforced yet
This is architectural reasoning, not coding.
RAG shape at this stage: System / Domain RAG
Instead of Service RAG, you create:
A domain‑level RAG index
It might include:
Business capability maps
Process diagrams
Existing monolith code (read‑only)
Glossary / taxonomy
Prior ADRs
This lets the LLM:
Identify bounded contexts
Suggest service candidates
Highlight coupling risks
At this stage, breadth beats precision.
Output of Phase 1 (human‑owned)
The LLM helps generate:
Candidate services
Responsibility statements
Context maps
High‑level APIs/events
Data ownership proposals
But humans decide.
Nothing is built yet.
Phase 2: Define boundaries (contracts before code)
This is the hinge phase.
What changes here
You stop reasoning about implementation and start reasoning about interfaces.
You freeze:
Service purpose
Inputs / outputs
Ownership
Non‑goals
This is where you earn future Service RAG safety.
RAG shape: Contract RAG
Now you create small, sharp artefacts:
OpenAPI specs
Event schemas
Command definitions
Data ownership statements
These live in a contracts folder, e.g.:
contracts/
└── payments/
     ├── refunds.openapi.yaml
     ├── settlement-events.avro
     └── ownership.md
The LLM is:
Allowed to reason across contracts
Not allowed to invent new cross‑service behaviour
This phase establishes:
“What collaboration looks like — without knowing how it’s implemented.”
Phase 3: First build (this is where Service RAG starts)
Now — and only now — Service RAG becomes valid.
Important difference vs “tweaks”
There is:
Little code
Little history
No tests yet
So Service RAG is seeded, not mature.
What goes into early Service RAG
Even on day one, the Service RAG includes:
✅ Service goal & scope doc
✅ Contracts (read‑only)
✅ Skeleton code / project structure
✅ Architecture constraints
✅ Known non‑goals
Example:
Plain Text
payments/
├── README.md ← purpose & rules
├── ARCH.md ← constraints
├── api/
├── domain/
└── tests/
The LLM is told:
“This service owns X. It must never do Y.”
That matters more than code at this stage.
How the LLM helps here
At first build, the LLM acts as:
A pair‑programming accelerator
A design explainer
A consistency checker
Not an autonomous agent.
Typical use:
Generate skeleton structure
Implement one use‑case at a time
Explain trade‑offs
Generate first tests
Every output is reviewed.
Phase 4: Normal evolution (where your earlier flow applies)
Now you have:
Tests
History
Clear service intent
Real Service RAG signal
This is where: ✅ Automated PRs
✅ Safe refactoring
✅ Multi‑agent parallelism
become sensible.
Why you don’t use Service RAG too early
If you jump straight to Service RAG during design:
❌ You freeze boundaries too soon
❌ You optimise locally before understanding global flows
❌ You encode mistakes into “memory”
❌ You get false confidence
Early design requires fluidity, not guardrails.
A simple rule of thumb
Design wide.
Contract sharp.
Build narrow.
Evolve safely.
Each step narrows the LLM’s world.
One‑page mental map
[ Domain understanding ]
        ↓
[ Service candidates ]
        ↓
[ Contracts defined ]
        ↓
[ Service skeleton ]
        ↓
[ Service RAG activated ]
        ↓
[ Safe evolution ]
The killer insight (this is the important bit)
RAG follows architecture — architecture does not follow RAG.
Service RAG is:
An enforcement mechanism
A memory optimiser
A safety boundary
It is not a design tool by itself.
Final plain‑English takeaway
For initial design, let the LLM see broadly and think like an architect.
Once boundaries are agreed, lock it inside a service and never let it escape.
